Question Text: Given the following URI https://courses.examsdigest.com/ccna, which part is the hostname?
Choices:
a. https
b. courses
c. courses.examsdigest.com
d. examsdigest.com
e. examsdigest.com/ccna
LLM Explanation: The hostname in the given URI is 'courses.examsdigest.com'. The hostname is the part of the URI that identifies the host that is being accessed. It comes after the scheme (https://) and before the path (/ccna).
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 28: Fundamentals of IP Version 4 Addressing and Routing', 'RFC 3986: Uniform Resource Identifier (URI): Generic Syntax']

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 443?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: HTTPS (Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure) uses port 443 by default. HTTPS is the secure version of HTTP, which uses SSL/TLS encryption to protect the data transmitted between a web browser and a web server. The other protocols mentioned use different default ports: HTTP uses port 80, SMTP uses port 25, and SSH uses port 22.
URLs: ['IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry: https://www.iana.org/assignments/service-names-port-numbers/service-names-port-numbers.xhtml', 'Cisco Networking Academy: Introduction to Networks v7.0 (ITN) - Chapter 9: Transport Layer']

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 80?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol) uses port 80 by default. It is the protocol used for transmitting web pages and other web content over the Internet. HTTPS uses port 443, SMTP uses port 25, and SSH uses port 22.

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 25?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol) is the protocol used for sending email messages between servers. It uses port 25 by default for non-encrypted communication. HTTP uses port 80, HTTPS uses port 443, and SSH uses port 22.

Question Text: Which of the following protocols uses the port 22?
Choices:
a. HTTPS
b. HTTP
c. SMTP
d. SSH
LLM Explanation: SSH (Secure Shell) is a network protocol that uses port 22 by default for secure remote login and other secure network services over an unsecured network. HTTPS uses port 443, HTTP uses port 80, and SMTP uses port 25.

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the SNMP protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: SNMP (Simple Network Management Protocol) uses UDP port 161 for general SNMP messages and requests between managers and agents. Port 161 is the standard port reserved for SNMP. The other ports mentioned are used for different protocols - port 20 for FTP data transfer, port 25 for SMTP, and port 160 is not a well-known port.
URLs: ['IETF RFC 1157 - A Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)', 'IANA Service Name and Transport Protocol Port Number Registry']

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the POP3 protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: POP3 (Post Office Protocol version 3) is an application-layer Internet standard protocol used by e-mail clients to retrieve e-mail from a server. POP3 uses TCP port 110 as its well-known port.

Question Text: Which of the following port numbers the DNS protocol uses?
LLM Explanation: The Domain Name System (DNS) protocol uses port 53 for its communication. DNS is used to translate human-readable domain names into IP addresses. Port 53 is the well-known port number reserved for both UDP and TCP communications of the DNS protocol.

Question Text: Which of the following options are things that a standard IP ACL could be configured to do? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. Match the exact source IP address
b. Match all IP addresses in a subnet with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
c. Match IP addresses 20.2.2.2 through 20.2.2.22 with one access-list command without matching other IP addresses
d. Match only the packet’s destination IP address
LLM Explanation: A standard IP access control list (ACL) can match the exact source IP address of packets using a command like 'access-list 1 permit 10.1.1.1'. It can also match only the packet's destination IP address by applying the ACL to inbound traffic on an interface. However, a standard ACL cannot match a range of addresses or a subnet without also including other IP addresses, as those capabilities require an extended ACL.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists (ACLs)', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']
SM - Description: Didn’t know that destination addresses cannot be matched and that subnets can be matched
Effect - Description of effects: Not knowing some capabilities of ACLs

Question Text: One of the differences between named and numbered ACLs is that named ACLS using ACL subcommands, not global commands, to define the action and matching parameters.
Choices:
a. TRUE
b. FALSE
LLM Explanation: The statement is true. Named ACLs use ACL subcommands within the named ACL configuration mode to define the action (permit or deny) and matching parameters (source IP, destination IP, protocol, etc.). In contrast, numbered ACLs use global configuration commands to define the action and matching parameters directly under the global configuration mode.
URLs: ['Cisco Press CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Part 1, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists (ACLs)', 'Cisco Documentation: Configure IP Access Control Lists (ACLs) - https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Given the following fields, which of those cannot be compared on an extended IP ACL?
Choices:
a. Application protocol
b. Destination IP address
c. Source IP address
d. URL
e. TOS Byte
LLM Explanation: Extended IP ACLs cannot compare URLs or the TOS byte. They can filter based on the application protocol (e.g., TCP, UDP), source IP address, and destination IP address. However, filtering based on URLs requires more advanced features like a firewall or web content filtering. The TOS (Type of Service) byte is also not a filterable field in standard extended IP ACLs.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 2, Chapter 16: IP Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/15-mt/sec-data-acl-15-mt-book/sec-create-ip-apply.html']
SM - Description: Didn’t know that extended all in Cisco can consider TOS
Effect - Description of effects: Not knowing some capabilities of ACLs

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #1: Permit packets from 186.33.2.3
ACL command #1: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3
b. access-list 1 deny 186.33.2.3
c. access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.0
d. access-list 1 deny 186.33.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a'. To permit packets from a specific IP address in a standard ACL, you use the 'permit' keyword followed by the IP address. In this case, the ACL command should be 'access-list 1 permit 186.33.2.3' to match the given criteria of permitting packets from 186.33.2.3.
URLs: ['Cisco Networking Academy: Introduction to Networks v7.0 - Chapter 7: Access Control Lists', 'Cisco IOS Security Command Reference: access-list (standard)']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #2: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57.2 as the first three octets
ACL command #2: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 1 permit 57.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 deny 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is 'a'. The ACL command 'access-list 1 permit 56.57.2.0 0.0.0.255' will permit packets from hosts with IP addresses starting with 56.57.2. The wildcard mask 0.0.0.255 matches any value in the last octet, allowing all hosts in the 56.57.2.0/24 subnet.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'Cisco IOS Access Lists Configuration Guide, https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/xe-16/sec-data-acl-xe-16-book.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line standard ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 1 in the command.
Criteria #3: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets
ACL command #3: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.255.255.255
b. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.255.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.58.0.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: To permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets, the correct wildcard mask should be 0.0.255.255. This wildcard mask matches any value in the last two octets while fixing the first two octets as 56.57. Option 'a' uses an incorrect wildcard mask that would match any value in the last three octets. Options 'c' and 'd' have incorrect wildcard masks and also do not match the 56.57 criteria in the first two octets.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #4: Permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5, sent to a web server in subnet 65.5.6.0/24
ACL command #4: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq 23
b. access-list 101 permit any any
c. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
d. access-list 101 deny tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is c. The ACL command 'access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www' matches the given criteria. It permits TCP traffic from the specific host 65.5.5.5 to any host in the 65.5.6.0/24 subnet, but only if the destination port is www (HTTP). This aligns with the requirement to permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5 to a web server in the specified subnet.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS Security Configuration Guide, Release 12.4 - Configuring IP Access Lists: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios/security/configuration/guide/12_4/sec_12_4_book/sec_access_list_overview.html', 'Cisco IOS IP Command Reference, Volume 1 of 3: Addressing and Services, Release 12.2 - IP Services Commands: access-list: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios/12_2/ipaddr/command/reference/fipras_r/1rfip1.html#wp1018617']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #5: Permit any and every IPv4 packet
ACL command #5: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit ip any any
b. access-list 101 deny ip any any
c. access-list 101 permit ip 0.0.0.0 any
d. access-list 101 permit ip any 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct command to permit any and every IPv4 packet in an extended ACL is 'access-list 101 permit ip any any'. This command uses the wildcard mask 'any' for both the source and destination IP addresses, effectively matching all IPv4 packets.

Question Text: Which of the following commands display the configuration of an IPv4 ACL, including line numbers? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. show running-config
b. show startup-config
c. show ip access-lists
d. show access-lists
LLM Explanation: The 'show ip access-lists' and 'show access-lists' commands both display the configuration of IPv4 ACLs, including the line numbers. The 'show running-config' and 'show startup-config' commands show the entire device configuration, which would include ACLs, but do not provide a focused view of just the ACL configuration with line numbers.

Question Text: Type the access-list command that permits all packets sent from hosts in subnet 14.15.16.0/24. Use the ACL number 50 for the ACL rule.
Choices:
a. access-list 50 permit 14.15.17.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 50 deny 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.255.255.255
d. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct command to permit all packets from the 14.15.16.0/24 subnet is 'access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255'. The ACL number 50 is used as specified. The subnet mask 0.0.0.255 is the wildcard mask equivalent of the /24 prefix, allowing any host within that subnet. The other options have incorrect wildcard masks or use 'deny' instead of 'permit'.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: IP Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: Given the following access-list command access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255, choose the exact range of IP addresses, matched by the command.
LLM Explanation: The access-list command 'access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255' matches the IP address range 192.168.4.0 - 192.168.4.255. The first part '192.168.4.0' specifies the network address, while the second part '0.0.0.255' is the wildcard mask. The wildcard mask determines which bits of the IP address can vary. In this case, only the last octet can vary from 0 to 255, resulting in the range 192.168.4.0 to 192.168.4.255.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text: The range of valid ACL numbers for standard numbered IP ACLs is:
LLM Explanation: The range of valid ACL numbers for standard numbered IP ACLs is 1-99 and 1300-1999. The 1-99 range is used for standard IP ACLs, while the 1300-1999 range is an expanded range also used for standard IP ACLs.

Question Text:
The ACL 55 on R1 has four statements, in the following order, with address and wildcard mask values as follows:
1. 20.0.0.0 0.255.255.255
2. 20.20.0.0 0.0.255.255
3. 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255
4. 2.2.2.0 0.0.0.255
If a router tried to match a packet sourced from IP address 20.20.20.20 using this ACL, which ACL statement does a router consider the packet to have matched?
Choices:
a. First statement
b. Second statement
c. Third statement
d. Forth statement
e. Implied deny at the end of the ACL
LLM Explanation: When a router processes an ACL, it goes through the statements in sequential order from top to bottom. It stops processing and considers the packet matched at the first statement where there is a match. In this case, the IP address 20.20.20.20 would match the third statement 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255 because the wildcard mask of 0.0.0.255 means that only the first three octets need to match exactly. The fourth octet can be anything from 0 to 255. So the router would consider this packet matched by the third ACL statement and stop processing further.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 2, by Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']
SM - Description: Calculates the first few options incorrectly
SM - Misunderstanding Reasons: An error related to misinterpreting IP addresses
Effect - Description of effects: Could have a major effect on ACL
Effect - Error Type: configuration issues, security issues, debugging delay

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, any source IP address with source port greater than 10455, a destination IP address 30.3.3.3 and a destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 28
b. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny tcp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 25 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is b. The access-list command 'access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25' matches the given criteria: - It denies UDP packets (not TCP as in option c) - The source IP is 'any' - The source port is greater than 10455 - The destination IP is the specific host 30.3.3.3 - The destination port equals 25 (not 28 as in option a) Option d is incorrect because it checks for source port greater than 25 instead of 10455.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS Security Command Reference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/security/a1/sec-a1-cr-book.html', 'Cisco IOS Access Lists Cheat Sheet: https://packetlife.net/media/library/13/Cisco_IOS_Access_Lists.pdf']

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, a source IP address 30.3.3.3 and a source port greater than 10455, any destination IP address 30.3.3.3 with destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 30
b. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 25 any eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.0.0.0 gt 10455 any eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct access list to deny the specified UDP packets is 'd'. It has the correct protocol (UDP), source IP address (30.3.3.3), source port (greater than 10455), destination IP (any), and destination port (equal to 25). Option 'a' has an incorrect destination port of 30. Option 'b' has an incorrect source port of greater than 25. Option 'c' has an incorrect source IP address of 30.0.0.0.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS Security Configuration Guide, Release 12.4 - Configuring IP Access Lists: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios/security/configuration/guide/12_4/sec_12_4_book/sec_access_list_ov.html', 'Cisco IOS IP Addressing Services Command Reference - access-list: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipaddr/command/ipaddr-cr-book/ipaddr-a1.html#wp3893541320']

Question Text: Choose the wildcard mask that matches all IP packets in the subnet 46.45.44.0, and mask 255.255.255.0.
LLM Explanation: The wildcard mask is the inverse of the subnet mask. Given the subnet mask is 255.255.255.0, the wildcard mask would be 0.0.0.255. This wildcard mask will match all IP addresses in the 46.45.44.0/24 subnet.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1, Chapter 12: IP Addressing and Subnetting', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/access-lists/26448-ACLsamples.html']
